By Peter Lewis
PUBLISHED:
13:26 EST, 22 November 2012
| UPDATED:
02:53 EST, 23 November 2012
Contemptuous: Brian Sewell has never been afraid of showing his disdain for many lauded artists
There are a few books, only a few, which make one wish to know the author in order to explore his thoughts and personality further. This is such a book - by the outstanding, most outspoken art critic of our time.Brian Sewell’s Outsider, his first volume of autobiography published last year, was a revelation - not only of his life as a repressed, then a released homosexual, but his exposure of the shady life behind the scenes at Christie’s, where he acquired his expertise in art history.He continues the story by painfully resigning from Christie’s because ‘I was damned for being queer’ and thus denied his own department and seat on the Board.Before certain news footage on television, viewers are warned of coming scenes that they may not wish to see. Likewise, I should warn you that there is total candour here about a sex life that some people may not wish to read of. Friend and spy: Art historian Professor Anthony Blunt
Sewell says writing his first volume about being both illegitimate and homosexual in youth ‘felt like self-administered psychoanalysis, deeply painful and disturbing’. He examines his later self just as dispassionately. ‘Casting aside decades of deceit and dissembling,’ he says he hopes to offer reassurance to other Outsiders.But you don’t have to be an outsider to find plenty to intrigue and challenge you besides what seems to have been his reckless and risky promiscuity.After Christie’s, he ‘scratched a living’ by becoming an art dealer on his own account, mainly in old drawings. He leads us into the wonderland of the Bond Street art market, populated with an extraordinary cast of suave and often shady characters with doubtful canvasses and suspect attributions to sell.Among fine art conmen are restorers, improvers and outright fakers of canvasses. Some brilliant fakers became so notorious - like the Hungarian Elmyr de Hory and the jocund Tom Keating - that after their deaths their work was itself faked to satisfy demand.The fascination of fine art faking is that there is scarcely ever such a thing as proof of authenticity. Signatures and aged canvas and paint can all be obtained or faked. Ultimately it comes down to the opinion of certain acknowledged experts. If Mr X says: ‘This is a Poussin,’ then it is a Poussin - or not, if a more highly rated Mr Y says it is not. Sewell’s scholarship and connoisseur’s ‘eye’ is so developed that at the National Gallery’s great Leonardo exhibition last winter, he ended by deciding that at least four of the prized exhibits were not by Leonardo at all.THE LIFE OF BRIANSewell is a classic car fan and likes to dirve a Mercedes Benz 560 SEC coupe barefootSince the age of 13, Sewell has been the proud owner of 16 dogs, all but two of them rescue dogs or straysIn 2008 Sewell played the omniscient controller in Big Brother Celebrity Hijack featuring Russell Brand and Peaches Geldof His master as a scholar and connoisseur was Anthony Blunt, director of the Courtauld Institute, keeper of the Queen’s pictures, the Fourth Man of the Cambridge spy ring and Sewell’s tutor and long-standing friend.Sewell was told of Blunt’s secret several years before his confession and consequent immunity from prosecution were made public by Margaret Thatcher. He was informed at Blunt’s request by an elderly Cambridge don, Andrew Gow, who may himself have been a member of the circle. During the subsequent hounding of Blunt, Sewell was conspicuously loyal to him, hiding and protecting his own mentor and thereby being hounded himself.He now says that Blunt ‘became a Communist spy of sorts’ although he had no politics and never voted at elections. ‘How could so scholarly a man put his career at risk for a political philosophy in which he had virtually no belief? The answer is Guy Burgess, who won from him undying loyalty… had Guy not been a Communist, nor would Anthony.’The picture of Blunt’s later years, expelled from all his posts and compelled to share a small flat with a male partner whom he no longer found tolerable, is a sad one. Worst of all, he had lost his standing as the ranking expert on Poussin.
One can sympathise with Sewell’s loyalty to a friend in public disgrace. But at no point does he reveal his private feelings about Blunt’s treachery, his secret he kept for so long.He clearly despises the once charming Burgess who became ‘a scruffy, drunken slob with the halitosis of a dragon’ - so he must find him an inadequate excuse for Blunt’s betrayal.
Neither does he tell us his personal feelings about Salvador Dali, for whose camera he used to pose naked - as did countless other young men who visited the painter at Cadaques on the Spanish coast. Voyeur: Salvador Dali at home in Cadaques
Voyeurism was Dali’s predilection - was there ever any film in his camera? - for he could not himself bear to be touched and claimed to be impotent.Sewell’s observations of Dali’s perverse tastes are sardonically amusing so that it comes as a surprise to read of his grief at Dali’s death. ‘The last of the great old masters,’ he calls him, a rare tribute from his pen.The overriding emotion that permeates these pages is contempt, the contempt of the historian for cynical trendsetters and gullible fashion-followers. Chief of his targets is the current art establishment, the Serotas and Rosenthals, the gallery directors, exhibition curators, the majority of art critics, the flatterers who inflate overpriced exhibition catalogues with cubic feet of hot air.It was a clique, 35-strong, of such figures who signed a letter demanding his removal as art critic of the Evening Standard in 1994. After ten years of trenchant reviews, they accused him of ‘insult and scurrility, posturing and prejudice’. The readers’ letters thought otherwise and his Editor declared that no editor would be seen to obey such a complaint. His reviews continued and a new sparkling selection of them is published by Quartet under the title Naked Emperors - which clearly sums up what he thinks of the ‘Young’ British Artists whom he discusses within.
There is scarcely a painter who meets with his approval. Not even David Hockney, whom he used to hail, surely with justice, as ‘one of the few great draughtsmen of the century’. But he sees no merit in the enormous Hockney landscapes that filled the walls and crowded the halls of the Royal Academy earlier this year. ‘No one who knows the Yorkshire Wolds has ever seen them clad in the ghastly gaudiness of Hockney’s vision… half of these pictures are fit only for the railings of Green Park.’ He rebukes the revered Lucien Freud for becoming ‘lazy’ in his drawing - ‘a vain man incapable of self-criticism’. Damien Hirst he at first rather admired before he turned his studio into a money-making factory of ‘extravagant goods desirable to footballers’ wives and collectors governed by envy. To own a Hirst is to tell the world that your bathroom taps are gilded and your Rolls-Royce is pink’. Critical: Sewell thought David Hockney's recent exhibits only fit for the railings at Hyde Park
As for Tracey Emin, now the RA’s Professor of Drawing, forsooth: ‘Skill, if she ever had any, has been usurped by celebrity, a celebrity nourished by deliberate outrage.’It must be discouraging to practice his critic’s craft on such unworthy material. He gets to the crux of the revolution of the Eighties when he says: ‘All an artist need do was to proclaim himself an artist and it followed that anything he made or did must necessarily be art - a simple logic merrily agreed by the empty-headed critics of the day.’In short, we have a new form of art-fakery which doesn’t even require the ability to draw or paint.No wonder Sewell looks back on his life as a sequence of failures - his expertise disregarded, his art pilgrimages turned into TV travelogues, his critical standards wasted on non-artists.But he has raised the art of literate vituperation to new enjoyable heights. May he continue to strip pretender emperors naked. Share or comment on this article
