After more than a week of the White House rushing toward imminent military action against Syria, President Obama's abrupt decision on Saturday to instead ask Congress for permission has left him with a high-risk gamble that could devastate his credibility if no action is ultimately taken.In a hastily announced statement by the President in the White House Rose Garden on Saturday, he argued that he did in fact have the power to act on his own. But faced with the prospect of taking action opposed by many Americans, the commander in chief tried to shift the burden and instead round up partners on Capitol Hill to share in that responsibility.The change of heart occurred on Friday evening after the President had a long walk around
the White House's grounds with his chief of staff. Obama then summoned some of his top aides and told them he now wanted to hold off on launching an
attack until Congress had its say. Change of direction: President Obama meets with senior advisers in the Oval Office on Friday night to discuss a new plan for the situation in Syria
